\begin_layout Itemize
(a) the energy states of the electron-pairs are at the lower edge of the
 energy gap and the excited single states are shown as a band starting at
 an energy of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 above the pair states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
At any non-zero temperature there will be a few occupied states in the single
 electron band.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We shall make the potential of film 1 positive with respect to film 2, so
 that all its energy states move to the left
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
(b) only a small current will flow from 2 to because the paired electrons
 on the left of 2 face the energy gap of 1 and only a few single electrons
 in the right band of 2 can tunnel to vacant states in 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
(c) where the relative shift in energy is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

the pair energy on the left of 2 is level with the edge of the right band
 of 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
it might be thought that electron pairs may now tunnel from 2 to 1.
 Since these electrons must tunnel into single electron states, each pair
 must first be split up at a cost of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 per electron.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Tunneling will only occur at (d), where the relative energy shift is 
\begin_inset Formula $2\Delta$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This enables the energy of a pair to be conserved because the single which
 has not tunneled gained 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta,$
\end_inset

 the electron that did loses 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 when dropped into the lowest occupied state of 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The tunneling current rises rapidally (e) , at this point the potential
 is 
